    sections: [
      { h: `Symptoms and their usual causes`, body: [`Forecast keeps missing: subjective stages and no exit criteria, so stage does not predict close.`, `Deals stuck in one stage: a real constraint (pricing, legal, a missing stakeholder) the process does not address.`, `Reps disagree on stage: criteria are too vague to be enforced consistently.`] },
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: `How do I know my sales process is broken?`, a: `The clearest signs are an unreliable forecast, deals that pile up in one stage or skip stages, and reps who disagree on what stage a deal belongs in. Each symptom traces to a specific root cause, usually vague criteria or activity-based stages.` },
      { q: `What is the most common cause of a broken process?`, a: `Stages named for seller activity ("demo scheduled") instead of buyer commitments, paired with exit criteria too vague to enforce. Together they make stage meaningless, which destroys forecast accuracy and lets unqualified deals clog the pipeline.` },
      { q: `Do I need to rebuild the whole process to fix it?`, a: `Usually not. Renaming stages around buyer commitments, rewriting exit criteria as objective tests, and enforcing them in the CRM fixes most breakage. The bigger change is cultural: inspecting the criteria weekly so the fix actually holds.` },
    ],
