    shortAnswer: `Handle "it's too expensive" by asking "compared to what?" to isolate whether it is a budget, competitor, or value concern, then returning to the quantified ROI the buyer agreed to and making the cost of the cheaper alternative concrete. The objection is almost always about price relative to perceived value, so rebuild the value rather than cutting the price.`,
    intro: [
      `"Too expensive" is the most common objection and the most misread. It is rarely about the absolute number and almost always about value.`,
      `Cutting price at this objection confirms the price was inflated and trains the buyer to push. Rebuild value instead.`,
    ],
    sections: [
      { h: `How to respond`, body: `Isolate, reframe, quantify.`, bullets: [
        `Isolate: "Compared to what, specifically?" Budget, a competitor, or doubt about value each needs a different answer.`,
        `Reframe to value: return to the quantified return the buyer agreed to; the price is a fraction of it.`,
        `Quantify the alternative: make the hidden cost of the cheaper option or of inaction concrete.`,
        `Trade if you move: never cut price without a give-get.`,
      ] },
      { h: `What not to do`, body: `Avoid the reflex mistakes.`, bullets: [
        `Do not cut price at the first push; it signals the number was soft.`,
        `Do not defend with a feature list; return to business value.`,
        `Do not accept "too expensive" at face value without isolating it.`,
      ] },
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: `How do I respond to "it's too expensive"?`, a: `Ask "compared to what?" to isolate the real concern, then return to the quantified ROI the buyer agreed to and make the cost of the cheaper alternative or of inaction concrete. The objection is about value, not the absolute number, so rebuild value rather than cutting price.` },
      { q: `Is "too expensive" really about price?`, a: `Rarely. It is almost always about price relative to perceived value. A buyer who sees a clear, quantified return does not find a fair price expensive. Cutting the number confirms it was inflated, so the right move is to rebuild the value case, not to discount.` },
      { q: `Should I discount when a buyer says the price is too high?`, a: `Not reflexively. First isolate the concern and return to value; the objection often dissolves. If a concession is genuinely warranted, trade it for a give-get like a longer term or faster signature. Discounting for free at the first push trains the buyer to keep pushing.` },
    ],
