    slug: `how-to-do-win-loss-analysis`,
    type: `guide`,
    title: `How to do win-loss analysis`,
    kw: `why we win and lose, deal review, patterns`,
    desc: `Do win-loss analysis that improves your win rate: interview won and lost buyers, look for patterns beyond price, and feed the insights into your process and playbooks.`,
    rookRuns: `win-loss patterns feed back into the process`,
    shortAnswer: `Do win-loss analysis by interviewing recent won and lost buyers about why they decided as they did, looking for patterns beyond the surface reason (which is usually not really price), and feeding the insights back into your process, messaging, and playbooks. Systematic win-loss analysis is one of the most reliable ways to lift win rate over time.`,
    intro: [
      `Reps report why they think they lost, but buyers often decided for entirely different reasons. Real win-loss analysis asks the buyers.`,
      `The patterns across many deals, not any single loss, are what tell you where to improve.`,
    ],
    steps: [
      { h: `Interview real buyers`, body: `Talk to recent won and lost buyers, ideally with a neutral interviewer, since buyers are more candid with someone other than the rep who worked the deal.` },
      { h: `Look past the stated reason`, body: `Buyers often cite price to be polite, but the real reason is frequently value, trust, or a missed stakeholder. Dig past the first answer.` },
      { h: `Find the patterns`, body: `Aggregate across many deals to see recurring themes: a competitor beating you on a specific dimension, a stage where deals consistently die, a persona you fail to win.` },
      { h: `Feed insights into the system`, body: `Turn patterns into changes: a new discovery question, a battlecard update, a process fix, revised messaging. Analysis that does not change anything is wasted.` },
    ],
    sections: [
      { h: `Common mistakes`, body: [`Relying on the rep's account of the loss rather than the buyer's, which is often wrong.`, `Doing the analysis but never feeding the insights back into the process, so nothing improves.`] },
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: `How do I do win-loss analysis?`, a: `Interview recent won and lost buyers about why they decided, ideally with a neutral interviewer, look past the stated reason to the real one, aggregate across deals to find patterns, and feed the insights into your process, messaging, and playbooks. Systematic win-loss analysis is one of the most reliable ways to lift win rate.` },
      { q: `Why interview buyers instead of relying on reps?`, a: `Because reps report why they think they lost, but buyers often decided for entirely different reasons, and they are more candid with a neutral interviewer than with the rep who worked the deal. The buyer's actual reasoning, especially when it differs from the rep's assumption, is where the real learning lives.` },
      { q: `Is price usually the real reason deals are lost?`, a: `Rarely. Buyers cite price to be polite, but the real reason is frequently a value gap, a trust issue, a missed stakeholder, or a competitor winning on a specific dimension. Good win-loss analysis digs past the stated reason to the real one, which is where the actionable insight to improve win rate is found.` },
    ],
